Already 374031 cases this week - the increase is surprising, I was wrong like most others here assuming it would be less than 400k. Shared defeat ;-)

I had been certain we'd see 300k to 400k cases, but instead, we're seeing a slight uptick in cases. 5 days into the forecast and we're already at 294.8k. We only have Friday and Saturday left, and they'd have to average 52.6k to keep cases under 300k. Sundays are low reporting days, and we already had our Sunday. Saturdays tend to be a bit lower than the preceding days of the week. But no Fri/Sat average has been under 52.6k for a very long time. Last week, at the recent minimum, the Fri/Sat average was ~54k. So, it seems extremely unlikely to me that today and tomorrow are going to come in lower than 52.6k, based on recent history. I think the total cases for the week is almost certainly going to be 400k to 500k.
410k weekly cases with 2 days left, seems more likely to remain above 400k.

Figured out that most of the bump today is coming from New York. However, even without the one day dump of 20k cases from New York new cases would be up. I think it's a coin-flip whether these cases get backdated before the question is resolved (or at all), and a coin-flip whether cases come down enough over the next couple days to drop it below 400k cases. Also possible New York hasn't worked out all its problems yet and may have more cases to dump tomorrow.
With 215K cases this week and 2 days to go. It is pretty safe to say that the total number will be between 300K and 400K.

Forces pushing cases up: B.1.1.7 variant, communities opening up. B.1.1.7 is about to become dominant in the US. In countries where it has become dominant, cases ceased declines and typically turned upward. In Michigan, on the leading edge of B.1.1.7 dominance in the US, cases/day have ticked up in the past couple weeks (see, e.g., https://twitter.com/EricTopol/status/1374187165932871680).

Checked in on the numbers and we are averaging 50,447 over the past 7 days meaning the expected continued average is 353,129 if nothing changed. The week-over-week change was -198 per day so we have definitely hit a trough and it is so unlikely that we drop to 40,000 per day as to be 0%. I still maintain a 2% chance that it is more than 400,000 in case things skyrocket but we would need an additional 6,695 cases per day over this week in order to reach that. There is a single day in the past week with only 35,370 cases so I adjusted the 2% chance to a 4% chance because this reporting day is not always so small (additional 14,000 case jump easily).

Point estimate 329,000. Weekly decline over last 4 weeks averages to 11.8% per week. Straight projection from week ending yesterday would take us just under 300,000. Downward pressure on that number: more vaccinations, warming weather. Upward pressure: spring break socializing, Texas and other states dropping mask mandates, new more contagious variants of virus, CDC ensemble models do not go under 300,000 for next 4 weeks.

The rates of COVID Infection as tracked by the CDC are projected to be right smack between 300-400K. The vaccination rates are increasing and even with college kids traveling for "spring break" or a variant going wild, it consistently has taken 3 weeks before behavioral changes impact the trajectory of the data. Two weeks out, the data is pretty predictable with COVID. https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#forecasting_weeklydeaths

Hard to read how this will unfold. Is there any reason why cases should drop rapidly from here? I don't see any news about new and/or increased restrictions. The main forecasts are now concerned with the winter (https://edition.cnn.com/2021/03/12/health/us-coronavirus-friday/index.html), suggesting that this current wave will continue to fizzle out. I have 300,000 - 400,000 as roughly twice as likely as the bin below because it will need a linear or accelerated drop in cases. Far from impossible especially with the noise about these figures.
7-day moving average 56599. *7=396K (bin 4), trend down. No reason, why it should go up significantly. Vaccine and weather should lead to a further decrease or at least flattening.

Correcting myself: If the decrease continues in a linear way - which we don't know, it might also go up again because of lightened restrictions (e.g. Texas) and mutations with higher reproduction number - we would reach 285k, so I give 20% to < 300k, 80% to 300-400k; guess this will remain suspenseful btw. 200-300 and 300-400 and need updates every other day.

Looking at the data for the past week (3/4 minus 2/25) we get 384,809 cases. These numbers have been falling across the US, but now states are reopening. The question is - how quickly will we see the effects of current policy?

States like Connecticut and Texas are opening and releasing all restrictions. NYC is opening movie theatres and event venues (33% capacity). Spring break runs from March 9th to April 21st. The two peak weeks will be the week of March 7-14. Holy Week is March 28 to April 3. Vaccinations continue to increase nationwide. In places like NYC, health dept. announced it will have enough vaccines to offer everyone by the end of April and vaccination sites are now running around the clock. Using a 50K daily cases base for now.

Too soon for vaccines to really be driving cases into the ground, though I do think they'll help keep things low. So many possible factors like seasonality, adherence to masking and best practices, a drop after a holiday spike, herd immunity from the recent spike, and vaccinations among healthcare workers at play. My guess for right now is just that we're leveling out a bit at somewhere around 475k weekly cases, and I would guess it's possible it could slowly decrease farther, but the last two dips downward bottomed out at 140k and 240k weekly cases, and I don't think we'll reach that point yet, it'll take more vaccinations to make that happen.
